      <c01 level="series">
        <did>
          <unittitle>Ralph Randles Stewart</unittitle>
        </did>
        <scopecontent>
          <p>The Ralph Stewart portion of the collection is separated into those materials relating to his personal life, his botanical interests and writings, and his teaching career in that area of India which became Pakistan in 1947.</p>
          <p>The personal portion of Ralph Stewart's collection consists primarily of writings and reflections created after his retirement. These writings reflect upon his early life and family in upstate New York and New York City. The period of his life spent while in India is not well documented in these papers. Most of Stewart's reflections were written late in his life and seem designed to be delivered as speeches or expanded upon as journal articles. The collection does include some contemporary material relating to travel in parts of northern India. There are also numerous letters relating to his travel experiences and to the people he met while returning to India late in 1944.</p>
          <p>Stewart was one of the earliest botanists to begin studying the flora of northern India. His writings document the findings of numerous trips away from Lahour. This portion of the collection consists of his published checklists and observations, some with annotations, and his notes. Most of the notes were written after retirement but a small amount of contemporary material is included.</p>
          <p>A short unpublished paper relating to a particular plant collecting trip and written by Isabelle Stewart (Ralph's first wife) is included in a folder at the end of his collection.</p>
        </scopecontent>
